    <p><strong>Load Up with Knowledge and Connections at the 2004 CEA Industry Forum</strong><br> by Dan Cole</p>
    Come in with your guns loaded.&nbsp;I love that expression, although I don’t know its origin and never really think of it in terms of a battle or a conflict. Rather, I think of it as the best possible way to approach any situation in life. And the 2005 International CES is no exception.
<P>As you gather your heavy artillery that helps you prep for the show, I want to give you what I believe is any consumer-tech executive’s best ammo: The <A href="http://www.ce.org/events/event_info/default.asp?eventID=IF04" target=_blank>2004 CEA Industry Forum</A> (FYI: Register by Oct. 8th to save $50 on conference registration.)</P>
<P>The information, contacts and overall experience you’ll garner October 18-20 in San Francisco is a bastion of high-tech knowledge on so many levels. So load up your chamber with these ‘bullets’ (Sorry, I couldn’t resist):</P>
<UL>
<LI>First, there’s the exclusive CEA market data released by economists about the upcoming 2004 holiday buying season and beyond. Make smart decisions about how to keep your company competitive in today’s challenging marketplace. </LI>
<LI>CEA’s division meetings that take place over the three days present an opportunity for your company to participate in shaping CEA’s public policy, technical standards, consumer outreach and research programs. </LI>
<LI>Network, and see, literally, hundreds of your industry peers—industry visionaries and retail executives alike. This non-competitive environment lets you get (and give) as much advice and information as you wish. Business and high-tech innovation almost always comes from mindshare, and I’ve seen so many brilliant seeds planted at this particular event. In addition to other attendees like you, you can collaborate and interact with sponsors such as <EM>ESPN HD</EM>, UPS, <EM>Partsearch Technologies </EM>and <EM>TWICE </EM>publications.Information-rich conferences get you up to speed with many of the markets within the consumer technology umbrella. You can get complete descriptions from the CEA website (<A href="http://www.CE.org" target=_blank>www.CE.org</A>), but let me fire off a few titles to give you an idea of the scope of this forum:<BR>- <EM>Connecting Products in the Digital Age<BR>- </EM><EM>Customer-Driven Innovation in the World of CE</EM> <BR>- <EM>Performance Homes: Consumer Electronics Drive Sales and Value while Enhancing ''Home Time''</EM> <BR>- <EM>Blue Laser Goes to Market<BR>- </EM><EM>Media Servers - What's Fact? What's Fiction?<BR>- </EM><EM>The Next Big Thing: Five Factors that will Affect the Coming of the ''Digital Home''<BR>- </EM><EM>Intellectual Property - Policy in the Making?<BR>- </EM><EM>The Road to Returns: An In-Depth Look at Consumer Behavior</EM> <BR>- <EM>Digital Cameras Get Competition</EM></LI></UL>
<P><A href="http://www.ce.org/events/event_info/default.asp?eventID=IF04" target=_blank>See all the details online</A>, and remember, you can save $50 on conference registration if you sign on by October 8. It’s among the smartest things you can do as you gear up—or get your guns loaded—for the 2005 International CES.<BR></P>
